	  The llllggggrrrreeeepppp command allows the user to search files for	a
	  specified text _s_t_r_i_n_g.  The name of any file that contains
	  the _s_t_r_i_n_g is	displayed.  Unlike grep(1), lgrep can search
	  files	with lines of unlimited	length.

	  The 'p' (print) option causes	up to _n_u_m_b_e_r printable
	  characters before and	after the _s_t_r_i_n_g to be displayed.

	  The 'c' (count) option causes	the program to continue
	  looking for additional matches after the first match rather
	  than going on	to the next file.  This	option also causes the
	  count	of the number of matches to be displayed with the file
	  name(s).

     EEEEXXXXIIIITTTT CCCCOOOODDDDEEEESSSS
	  The exit status is 0 if any matches are found, 1 if none, 2
	  if any file could not	be read	(regardless of matches), and
	  255 if a command line	error was detected.

     LLLLIIIIMMMMIIIITTTTAAAATTTTIIIIOOOONNNNSSSS
	  Currently, llllggggrrrreeeepppp does	not support regular expressions	and
	  the _s_t_r_i_n_g must contain only printable (040 (space) through
	  0176 (tilde))	characters.

